"Diagnosis"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"777e5d",
"children":[
"Clinical manifestations may include asthma, ",
{
"type":"no-wrap",
"children":[
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"chronic obstructive pulmonary disease",
"children":[
"COPD"
]
},
","
]
},
" constrictive bronchiolitis, rhinitis, and ",
{
"type":"no-wrap",
"children":[
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"diffuse parenchymal lung disease",
"children":[
"DPLD"
]
},
"."
]
},
" Symptom onset following exposure can be acute (reactive airways disease/small airways dysfunction as occurs in acute chlorine gas exposure) as well as prolonged or subacute with a significant latent period (as with asbestosis)."
]
},
{
"type":"inline-wrap",
"wrapId":"1",
"contentIds":[
"mk19_bb_pm_s9_inline_t1"
],
"forceOpen":true
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"3e9055",
"children":[
"A positive response to a specific inhalation challenge test is the “gold standard” for diagnosis but not always necessary."
]
}
]
},
{
"type":"section",
"id":"mk19_bb_pm_s9_2",
"title":{
"__html":"Treatment"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"4c4ac0",
"children":[
"Treatment"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"cbf34b",
"children":[
"The overriding principle is discontinuing the exposure. Occupational asthma and reactive airways dysfunction syndrome are treated with inhaled glucocorticoids."
]
},
{
"type":"heading",
"class":"tricked",
"children":[
"Don't Be Tricked"
]
},
{
"type":"list",
"class":"tricked",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"b97f56",
"children":[
"The incidence of ",
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"tuberculosis",
"children":[
"TB"
]
},
" is increased in those with silicosis and should be evaluated in patients with silicosis, fever, and cough."
]
},
" "
]
}
]
},
{
"type":"section",
"id":"mk19_bb_pm_s9_3",
"title":{
"__html":"Test Yourself"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"7866cc",
"children":[
"Test Yourself"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"15e143",
"class":"test",
"children":[
"A previously healthy 45-year-old man has a cough of 6 months' duration. He is a lifelong nonsmoker and works as an automobile spray painter. Physical examination discloses a few expiratory wheezes. ",
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"forced expiratory volume exhaled in 1 second",
"children":[
"FEV",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"sub",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"1"
]
}
]
},
" is 0.65 and FEV",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"sub",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"1"
]
},
"/",
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"forced vital capacity",
"children":[
"FVC"
]
},
" ratio is 65% of predicted, with a 22% improvement after bronchodilator administration."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"aa5352",
"class":"test_answer",
"children":[
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"b",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"Answer:"
]
},
" ",
"For diagnosis, choose occupational asthma. For management, select spirometry or ",
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"peak expiratory flow",
"children":[
"PEF"
]
},
" measurement before and after work (or during vacation)."
]
}
]
}
]
